      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25897659#p25897659" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">grizzlyaddams</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">But all the people within the government commiting treason against our constitution, that's perfectly fine...<br /><br />/s (Just in case)</div><br /><br />Who's interpretation of the constitution.  There are plenty of conflicting views on exactly what the constitution says.  The constitution itself in Article III puts the Supreme Court in charge of resolving the question of who is right.  The NSA's ruling in Smith v Maryland supports what the NSA has done as constitutional.<br /><br />I personally think that Smith v Maryland is wrong, and with the advantage of hindsight and current issues as an example, it seems absurdly wrong.<br /><br />However, my opinion has no legal value beyond my ability to vote for representatives that will try to restore our rights.<br /><br />The government is wrong in what they are doing, but they aren't breaking the law, nor are they violating the interpretation of the constitution made by those the constitution grants the authority to interpret it.  They aren't committing treason.<br /><br />Snowden's leaks have done some good.  However, his leaks cover far more than they need to in order to expose such activity, and they are narrow in that they only cover the surveillance activities of the US and their allies.  There would seem to be considerable evidence that Snowden's goals go beyond his stated goal of being a whistle blower.<br /><br />Snowden betrayed his oath to keep the government's secrets.  He betrayed his coworkers by getting them to give him their passwords and then using them to get documents hew wasn't authorized to access (and probably getting those people fired due to them losing their clearances).  Are you surprised that people in the intelligence community feel betrayed by him and want him brought to justice?<br /><br />What he did in disclosing these programs, only those of American and their allies, and then fleeing to those that are arguably our enemies could very well be interpreted as treason.<br /><br />And despite the comments of the author and many on this thread, suggesting that someone should be captured, tried by a jury of their peers, and the executed for their crimes isn't a threat of murder.  It's not an example of a government agency out of control.  It's an example of someone that despite their anger is suggesting that justice should be found through due process of the law.
      
    </div>
