  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="fxds"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=12725&amp;sid=f0c298d4d33b37fc59279c7b706622ca">fxds</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Tribunus Militum</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/12/former-cia-chief-snowden-should-be-hanged-by-the-neck-until-dead/?comments=1&post=25903871#comment-25903871" title="2013-12-20T11:45:55-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Dec 20, 2013 11:45 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25900387#p25900387" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Stormicles</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">My opinion is valid, if you don't agree, fine. Call me an idiot, because of it? Piss off!</div><br />Sure, your opinion is valid *as your opinion*.  It's not valid as a basis for legal action against Snowden, because it's based on the dictionary definition of the word &quot;treason&quot; rather than the legal definition of the crime of treason as spelled out in the US Constitution.  The authors of the constitution deliberately chose a narrow definition for the crime of treason for the same reason they chose many other positions, to limit the power of the federal government.  They wanted to make sure the crime of treason couldn't be used at the whim of government leaders to attack their opponents based on the vague and subjective dictionary definition.<br /><br />None of that makes you an idiot, unless you continue to believe that Snowden is guilty of the crime of treason based on the dictionary definition, and that he should therefore suffer the stated punishment, which is death.  You know, like those idiots Woolsey, Bolton, Boehner, Nelson, Schhock, Feinstein, etc.  Fortunately for them, being an idiot (or a liar) doesn't make one a traitor.  Just a politician.
      
    </div>
