<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="8"
  data-post-negative="0"
  data-post-positive="8"
  data-post-id="25904123" data-poster-id="12725" id="comment-25904123">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="fxds"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=12725&amp;sid=f0c298d4d33b37fc59279c7b706622ca">fxds</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Tribunus Militum</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/12/former-cia-chief-snowden-should-be-hanged-by-the-neck-until-dead/?comments=1&post=25904123#comment-25904123" title="2013-12-20T12:10:48-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Dec 20, 2013 12:10 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25901069#p25901069" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">PeterWimsey</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It's not a fact.  Almost every expert in 4th amendment law believes that what the NSA did was constitutional.  They also believe that the recent opinion from Judge Leon is wrong.  And they are probably correct in both points.</div><br />That's a bit disingenuous.  &quot;Almost every expert&quot; might indeed say the NSA's mass surveillance is constitutional, but you left off the critical second half of the sentence, &quot;under the 'third party doctrine' established by the Supreme Court in Smith v. Maryland.&quot;  You also fail to mention that a number of Supreme Court justices appear to be thinking about the question of how that decision still applies given the advances in technology since 1979 that now allow for massive dragnet surveillance that was impossible and unthinkable back then.  Hell, Justice Sotomayor voiced that question explicitly in her concurring opinion in U.S. v Jones last year, writing &quot;It may be necessary to reconsider the premise that an individual has no reasonable expectation of privacy in information voluntarily disclosed to third parties.&quot;<br /><br />In other words, the constitutionality of the NSA's mass surveillance is based on Supreme Court interpretation of the 4th Amendment, rather than the wording of the Amendment itself.  And that's correct, since the Supreme Court is the arbiter of legal interpretation of the Constitution.  But we can't ignore the fact that the Court has changed its interpretation of numerous clauses of the Constitution over the years, and that there's enough indication that the Justices are reconsidering the third party doctrine to make it a valid consideration.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
