      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/12/former-cia-chief-snowden-should-be-hanged-by-the-neck-until-dead/?comments=1&post=25904549#comment-25904549" title="2013-12-20T13:03:46-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Dec 20, 2013 1:03 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      Just wanting to back up for a minute:<br /><br />To date, Snowden hasn't actually leaked anything detrimental to the security of this country, right?<br /><br />In other words... he hasn't exposed undercover agents in the field, vital operations, opening up areas for some form of attack.... all he's leaked so far is NSA's own domestic-spying operations along with things like 'They got the German president's Blackberry bugged!'.<br /><br />I think those are embarrassing things to reveal, and exposing them creates a lot of grief for a TON of people... but I don't see it as treason until a fellow American is seriously hurt by it.  <br /><br />If Snowden were to leak some info that leads to some Benghazi-type event and Americans are hurt or killed or put in harm's way... ok, then we can call him a traitor.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
