  data-post-score="3"
  data-post-negative="-1"
  data-post-positive="4"
  data-post-id="25904723" data-poster-id="341954" id="comment-25904723">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="Venick"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=341954&amp;sid=f0c298d4d33b37fc59279c7b706622ca">Venick</a></span><span class="rank">Wise, Aged Ars Veteran</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/12/former-cia-chief-snowden-should-be-hanged-by-the-neck-until-dead/?comments=1&post=25904723#comment-25904723" title="2013-12-20T13:23:00-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Dec 20, 2013 1:23 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25902581#p25902581" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">flatrock19</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The government is wrong in what they are doing, but they aren't breaking the law, nor are they violating the interpretation of the constitution made by those the constitution grants the authority to interpret it.  They aren't committing treason.<br /><br />Snowden's leaks have done some good.  However, his leaks cover far more than they need to in order to expose such activity, and they are narrow in that they only cover the surveillance activities of the US and their allies.  There would seem to be considerable evidence that Snowden's goals go beyond his stated goal of being a whistle blower.<br /><br />Snowden betrayed his oath to keep the government's secrets.  He betrayed his coworkers by getting them to give him their passwords and then using them to get documents hew wasn't authorized to access (and probably getting those people fired due to them losing their clearances).  Are you surprised that people in the intelligence community feel betrayed by him and want him brought to justice?<br /><br />What he did in disclosing these programs, only those of American and their allies, and then fleeing to those that are arguably our enemies could very well be interpreted as treason.<br /><br />And despite the comments of the author and many on this thread, suggesting that someone should be captured, tried by a jury of their peers, and the executed for their crimes isn't a threat of murder.  It's not an example of a government agency out of control.  It's an example of someone that despite their anger is suggesting that justice should be found through due process of the law.</div><br /><br />Law is constantly changing; sometimes it takes incredible sacrifices and significant events. Legal becomes illegal, legal to illegal. There are always amends and abolishing. Take a look back and find an example in the history of law. You know we generally, inevitably steer towards better morals. I'd hope the definition of what is found legal here continually adapts by those with the knowledge, experience, and integrity to make that decision. <br /><br />You find the government doing wrong. An elaboration is unnecessary. There is a sense of controversy, a feeling of a loophole found. If nothing is found illegal, something might need to be reformed in order to understand, regulate, or do away with.<br /><br />I cannot speculate on Snowden or imply his actions deceitfully malicious. Even so, he brought insight. But betrayal has a powerful connotation reserved for the most heinous. And if through reciting an oath you find something immoral, you must make a choice of doing one evil or another - blindly follow and uphold your promise or break it. A good soldier follows orders. A better one knows when to ignore them.<br /><br />I care little of Snowden. Whatever sacrifice he made or justice that is brought to him, I only hope it makes the country and the world better.
      
    </div>
