 with this info and with the info that you turned a blind eye to this proof&quot;.  Going to the press should have been his LAST resort.  <br /><br />That's what he SHOULD have done.  He didn't.  He just went blabbing to the press straightaway because HE had personal issues with what was happening.  As noted elsewhere, he violated his oath(s) and he violated US federal law(s) in doing so.  So far as I can tell he never tried to go via the legal 'whistleblowing' route first.  So I would say he never intended to blow the whistle, so much as cause fundamental harm purely on the strength of his own personal opinions, something I'd say he was never morally entitled to do.
      
    </div>
