    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25905333#p25905333" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">cyber|kinetic</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25902595#p25902595" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">jdale</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25902147#p25902147" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">cyber|kinetic</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">If Snowden's goal was to 'promote public discussion' then that isn't enough to justify what he's done.  If he felt he had reasonable legal or constitutional objections to what he saw happening, I'm sure there were ways to raise those issues - perhaps via a congressional oversight committee - that didn't have to cause such harm to the NSA's mission (which remains a valid one)?  The fact is he went public, playing his entire pocketful of aces, in one go.  He always understood the damage he was going to cause, and knew it would go far beyond any reasonable concerns over NSA misbehaviour, etc.  So I don't believe he was simply acting out of concern for over-reach or even for fundamental constitutional breaches.  Were that the case, he had smarter avenues to pursue (one of which was as mentioned above).<br /><br />Snowden is a traitor, plain and simple, and the only appropriate penalty for such treachery is the death penalty.</div><br /><br />Go to the congressional oversight committee? And do what, convince Senator Wyden there were abuses going on? Senator Wyden had already been warning people of just that and was unable to get anyone to listen.</div><br />In the first instance, he hides his data, goes abroad if necessary to ensure his own freedom long enough to do his job, then he a) goes to the relevant Congressional committees or chairmen, and b) he goes to the White House (relevant person/s).  He says &quot;I have overwhelming proof of breachs of law and the consitution that I am prepared to show you, on the understanding that you act appropriately.  If you do not act appropriately THEN I will go public with this info and with the info that you turned a blind eye to this proof&quot;.  Going to the press should have been his LAST resort.  <br /><br />That's what he SHOULD have done.  He didn't.  He just went blabbing to the press straightaway because HE had personal issues with what was happening.  As noted elsewhere, he violated his oath(s) and he violated US federal law(s) in doing so.  So far as I can tell he never tried to go via the legal 'whistleblowing' route first.  So I would say he never intended to blow the whistle, so much as cause fundamental harm purely on the strength of his own personal opinions, something I'd say he was never morally entitled to do.</div><br /><br />That's interesting. So you believe it would be ok for him to go public, he just had to warn someone in advance of doing so and give them a chance to do the right thing?<br /><br />What if someone else had come forward first, someone in the NSA, using appropriate whistleblowing channels? Reporting to the correct people? If those correct people (e.g. congressional committee chairmen) did not respond appropriately, and instead the NSA fired those whistleblowers, searched their homes, revoked their security clearance, interfere with their finding new jobs, etc. If that had happened, could Snowden have treated that as the one chance for the right channels to do the right thing? Or did he have to try it personally?<br /><br />Because that's what happened. J. Kirk Wiebe, William Binney, Ed Loomis, Russ Tice, Thomas Andrews Drake...  There's quite a history of NSA employees trying to do the right thing, getting punished for it, having little impact.<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Binney_%28U.S._intelligence_official%29">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Bi ... fficial%29</a><!-- m --><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trailblazer_Project">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trailblazer_Project</a><!-- m --><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russ_Tice">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russ_Tice</a><!-- m --><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Andrews_Drake">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Andrews_Drake</a><!-- m --><br /><br />I don't know why Snowden would look at that record and say, &quot;But surely with me it will be different.&quot;
      
    </div>
